**Definition (Circulant)** A _Circulant matrix_
is an $n Ã— n$ Toeplitz matrix
which "wraps around":
$$
\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}
a_0 & a_{n-1} & â‹¯ & a_1 \\
a_1 & a_0 & â‹± & a_2 \\
â‹® & â‹± & â‹± & â‹®  \\
a_{n-1} & â‹¯ & a_1 & a_0 \end{bmatrix}}_C
$$

Here is an example construction:
```julia
function circulantmatrix(ğš)
    n = length(ğš)
    C = zeros(eltype(ğš), n, n)
    for k = 1:n, j = 1:n
        C[k,j] = ğš[mod(k-j,n)+1]
    end
    C
end
ğš = [1,3,2,5,9] # coefficients
C  = circulantmatrix(ğš)
```


**Theorem (Circulant diagonalization)**
The DFT matrix diagonalises a Circulant matrix:
$$
C Q_n = Q_n \begin{bmatrix} a(1) \\ & â‹± \\ && a(Ï‰^{n-1}) \end{bmatrix}
$$
where
$$
a(z) = âˆ‘_{k=0}^{n-1} a_k z^k
$$
and $Ï‰ = \exp(2Ï€{\rm i}/n)$.

**Proof**
Consider the circulant shift matrix:
$$
\underbrace{
\begin{bmatrix}
0   &&& 1
\\ 1 \\
& â‹± \\ &&1 & 0
\end{bmatrix}
}_S
$$
so that $C = a_0 I  + a_1 S + â‹¯ + a_{n-1} S^{n-1}$. Note $S$ is a permutation matrix, hence it is orthogonal ($S^âŠ¤ S = I$),
normal, and is diagonalisable. We verify directly that $Q_n$ is its eigenvector matrix (use the fact that $Ï‰^{-(n-j)} = Ï‰^j$):
$$
\begin{align*}
S Q_n &= {1 \over âˆšn} \begin{bmatrix} 1 & Ï‰^{-(n-1)} & Ï‰^{-2(n-1)} & â‹¯ & Ï‰^{-(n-1)^2} \\
